I DECOMPOSITION ON
BRIDGELAND MODULI SPACES OVER SURFACES
WANMIN LIU
Abstract. We nd a decomposition formula of the local BayerMacr`
map for the nef line bundle theory on the Bridgeland moduli space over a
surface. If there is a global BayerMacr` map, then such a decomposition
gives a precise correspondence from Bridgeland walls to Mori walls. As
an application, we compute the nef cone of the Hilbert scheme S
[n]
of
n-points over special kinds of a bered surface S of Picard rank 2.
1. Introduction
Let S be a smooth projective surface over C. Let M be the Gieseker
moduli space of semistable sheaves with xed Chern character ch over S.
One viewpoint for studying the birational geometry of M is to study the
classication of line bundles on M and dierent cones inside its real Neron
Severi group N
1
(M), such as the nef cone Nef(M ), and pseudoeective
cone E(M). Another viewpoint is introduced by Bridgeland [Bri07] with
the idea of enlarging the category of coherent sheaves Coh(S) to its bounded
derived version D
b
(S) and studying moduli spaces of Bridgeland semistable
objects in D
b
(S). Let be a Bridgeland stability condition, and let M
(ch)
be the moduli space of -semistable objects in D
b
(S) with the same invariant
ch. The collection of all stability conditions forms an interesting parameter
space Stab(S), which is a C-manifold. Bridgeland identied M as M
(ch),
for in a special chamber inside Stab(S). He envisioned that the wall-
chamber structures of Stab(S) will recover birational models of M.
When S is the projective plane P
2
and ch = (1, 0, n), the moduli space
M is the Hilbert scheme P
2[n]
of n-points over P
2
. Arcara, Bertram, Coskun,
and Huizenga [ABCH13] found a precise relation between Bridgeland walls
inside Stab(P
2
) with respect to (1, 0, n) and Mori walls inside E(P
2[n]
) (see
Corollary 4.14). Bertram and Coskun [BC13] generalized the speculation to
other rational surfaces. Bayer and Macr` [BM14a, BM14b] linked the two
viewpoints by establishing a line bundle theory on Bridgeland moduli spaces.
Let =
,
be the stability condition constructed by Arcara and Bertram
[AB13], which depends on an ample line bundle and another line bundle
over S. Assume that is in a chamber C. Bayer and Macr` constructed
a map by sending to a nef line bundle
on M
(ch), which is called the
local BayerMacr` map. The line bundle
only depends on the chamber C.

In this article, we nd a decomposition of the line bundle
,
. The de-
composition is classied into two cases according to the given Chern charac-
ter ch. The case for objects supported in dimension 1 is given in Lemma 4.5.
The case for objects supported in dimension 2 is given in Lemma 4.8. In this
case, an equivalent decomposition is also obtained by Bolognese, Huizenga,
Lin, Riedl, Schmidt, Woolf, and Zhao [BHL+16, Proposition 3.8.]. If there
is a global BayerMacr` map, we then obtain the precise correspondences
from Bridgeland walls to Mori walls for two such cases (see respectively,
Theorems 4.10 and 4.13). By Mori walls, we mean the walls that appear on
the stable base locus decomposition of the pseudoeective cone E(M).
As an application of the main theorem, we compute the nef cone of the
Hilbert scheme S
[n]
of n-points over special kinds of a bered surface S in
Theorem 5.2. Here S is either the Hirzebruch surface or an elliptic surface
over P
1
with a global section of Picard rank 2. The example suggests that, to
obtain the extremal nef line bundle, we cannot assume that the is parallel
to .
Some of the techniques discussed in this article have been partially gen-
eralized by Coskun and Huizenga [CH15] to compute the nef cone of certain
Gieseker moduli spaces.
Outline of the article. Section 2 is a brief review of the notion of Bridge-
land stability conditions. Section 3 is a brief review of Bayer and Macr`s
line bundle theory on Bridgeland moduli spaces. The main theorems on the
BayerMacr` decomposition are given in Section 4. In Section 5, we provide
an application of the main theorem. Some background on the large-volume
limit is given in Appendix A. Some parallel computations by using

(B.1)) for a K3 surface are given in Appendix B.
